      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug decode-hardfault \"Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/PWR/FAULTING/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/FAULTING.elf\"",
        "description": "Decode hardfault via gdb \u2014 read SCB/CFSR/HFSR/MMFAR/BFAR + callstack",
        "timeout": 60000
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "The right recipe is `stm32 debug decode-hardfault` \u2014 it spawns a fresh gdbserver + arm-gdb, reads CFSR/HFSR/MMFAR/BFAR/SCB, captures the callstack, applies Cortex-M decode rules, then tears down. I need the ELF path to proceed.\n`FAULTING.elf` is the obvious candidate given the project name. Running the decode now:\nThe gdbserver failed to connect \u2014 no ST-LINK probe was detected. The error is:\n\n```\nST-Link enumeration failed\nError in initializing ST-LINK device. Reason: ST-LINK DLL error.\n```\n\n**What's happening:** `ST-LINK_gdbserver` exited with code 2 before reaching the listener-ready state. It found no probe to attach to.\n\n**Check these in order:**\n\n1. **USB connection** \u2014 is the NUCLEO physically connected? Try unplugging and re-plugging the USB cable (ST-LINK side, not the target USB if separate).\n2. **Probe list** \u2014 run `stm32 prog list-probes` to see if the ST-LINK is visible at the programmer layer. If it shows up there but gdbserver still fails, the issue is firmware-specific to the gdbserver DLL.\n3. **ST-LINK firmware** \u2014 your bench F401RE has a known `DEV_USB_COMM_ERR` on its onboard ST-Link V2J28M17 (per your memory notes \u2014 firmware upgrade is pending). If you're using that board's ST-Link to program/debug the FAULTING target, that's the likely root cause. Use STM32CubeProgrammer's **\"Firmware upgrade\"** tab to bring V2J28M17 up to the latest firmware.\n4. **Other ST-LINK probe** \u2014 if you have an external ST-LINK/V3 or a different NUCLEO, connect that and re-run.\n\nOnce the probe is enumerable, re-run the same command and I'll decode the CFSR/HFSR/fault address dump."
}